04789nam a22007335i 9780801465833DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013943960  a97808014658337 a10.7591/97808014658332doi  a(DE-B1597)478336  a(OCoLC)979627763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aTK9153b.K38 2016 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a621.482231 aKaufman, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProject Plowshare :bThe Peaceful Use of Nuclear Explosives in Cold War America /cScott Kaufman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b8 halftones, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Promoting the Peaceful Atom -- t1. A Plan of Biblical Proportions -- t2. Just Drop Us a Card -- t3. A Program on Hold -- t4. From Moratorium to Test Ban -- t5. The Complexities of Canal Construction -- t6. Nuclear Testing, Nonproliferation, and Plowshare -- t7. Making Headway? -- t8. Plowshare Goes Down Under -- t9. Dead as a Doornail -- tConclusion: Back from the Dead? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInspired by President Dwight D. Eisenhower's "Atoms for Peace" speech, scientists at the Atomic Energy Commission and the University of California's Radiation Laboratory began in 1957 a program they called Plowshare. Joined by like-minded government officials, scientists, and business leaders, champions of "peaceful nuclear explosions" maintained that they could create new elements and isotopes for general use, build storage facilities for water or fuel, mine ores, increase oil and natural gas production, generate heat for power production, and construct roads, harbors, and canals. By harnessing the power of the atom for nonmilitary purposes, Plowshare backers expected to protect American security, defend U.S. legitimacy and prestige, and ensure access to energy resources.Scott Kaufman’s extensive research in nearly two dozen archives in three nations shows how science, politics, and environmentalism converged to shape the lasting conflict over the use of nuclear technology. Indeed, despite technological and strategic promise, Plowshare’s early champions soon found themselves facing a vocal and powerful coalition of federal and state officials, scientists, industrialists, environmentalists, and average citizens. Skeptical politicians, domestic and international pressure to stop nuclear testing, and a lack of government funding severely restricted the program. By the mid-1970s, Plowshare was, in the words of one government official, "dead as a doornail." However, the thought of using the atom for peaceful purposes remains alive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNuclear energyxIndustrial applicationsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aNuclear energyxIndustrial applicationszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNuclear explosionsxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aNuclear explosionszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aHistory Of Science. 4aMilitary History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146583340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801465833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801465833/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-